 variant of   Walsh  ."]},{"name":"McBratney","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Breatnaigh</b> ‘son of the Briton’ (referring to the Welsh of Strathclyde). Compare   Walsh   and   Galbraith  ."]},{"name":"Welsh","meanings":["Scottish, English, and Irish: ethnic name from Middle English <i>welshe</i> (Old English <i>wēalisc</i>, <i>wēlisc</i>) ‘foreign, Welsh’, for someone from Wales or a speaker of the Welsh language. Compare   Walsh   and   Wallace  .","Americanized form of German   Welsch  .","Americanized form of Ukrainian and Jewish (from Ukraine)   Voloshin   or its Polish variant <b>Wołoszyn</b> (see   Woloszyn  )."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","meanings":["A name corrpted from Hannah, q.v. It is also found several times in a male name. From Ann, Anne, we have as nicknames Nan and Nancy"],"variants":[{"name":"Nancy","meanings":["Of uncertain origin. From the 18th century it is clearly used as a pet form of   Ann   (  see  Nan  ), but it may originally have been a similar formation deriving from the common medieval given name   Annis  , a vernacular form of   Agnes .  Nowadays it is an independent name, and was especially popular in America in the 1930s, 40s, and 50s."]},{"name":"Nan","meanings":["Originally a pet form of   Ann   (for the initial <i>N-</i>,  compare  Ned  ). It is now also widely used as a short form of   Nancy ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Anne Walsh was born in 1382, in Glos-sur-Lisieux, Calvados, France. She married John Weston in 1400. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died about 1402, in Boston, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 21."},"et":{"1382–Abt. 1402":"1382–umbes 1402","1378–1431":"1378–1431","1410–1516":"1410–1516","1382–1402":"1382–1402","1402":"1402","1400":"1400","1378":"1378","Abt. 1402":"umbes 1402","1410":"1410","1431":"1431","1382":"1382","1516":"1516","Boston, Lincolnshire, England":"Boston, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Glos, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, France":"G